You could also do it like this:<p><pre><code>    var closures = [];
    for (var i = 0; i < 10; i++)
    {
        var j = i;
        closures[i] = (function (k) { return function() { alert(k); })(j);
    }
    closures[0](); // outputs 0
</code></pre>
The issue is that the var here is passed by reference.  Ie, all 10 closures refer to the SAME "i" variable.  So, when i is incremented, they see that it's been incremented.<p>Outputing 9 is actually correct in the first case.  If you want to trap the current value, you need to copy the value to a new reference, ie, by making it the argument of a function with a new scope.
